FEVER, UNDIAGNOSED - USA (NEW MEXICO) (02)
********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
<http://www.fas.org/promed/ahead>
See Also
Fever, undiagnosed - USA (New Mexico) 981214124706

[This report has drawn a plethora of suggestions for the etiologic
agent, covering the gamut from arboviruses in search of a disease,
through leptospirosis -- 50% of the cases seen in Hawaii are reported
to have thrombocytopenia -- to "It's a hantavirus after all." Below
are a selection of responses - Mod.JW
[1
Date: Mon, 14 Dec 1998 16:15:26 -0600
From: "Dr. Norman Ronald" <n-ronald@TVMDL.TAMU.EDU>

The Infectious and Parasitic Disease knowledge base lists the
following diseases known to occur in the U.S.A. which have a perfect
match with thrombocytopenia and the clinical signs described:
Brucellosis
Endemic Relapsing Fever
Typhoid
Toxoplasmosis
Flea Borne Typhus
Ehrlichiosis
RMSF [Rocky Mountain Spotted Fever
Squirrel Borne Epidemic Typhus
Viral Hepatitis A
Cache Valley Fever
Lack of mention of any type of rash would seem to raise Brucellosis,
Ehrlichiosis and Cache Valley to a higher suspicion level than the
other diseases.
This list is based on the old DOS version. I will hand audit the
rewrites to be used in the Window's version and send an addendum if
one is necessary.
--
N.C. Ronald PhD
Editor Infectious and Parasitic Diseases
TVMDL-TAMU
College Station, Texas 77843
Tel: 409-845-3414
<n-ronald@TVMDL.TAMU.EDU>
