[2
Date: Mon, 14 Dec 1998 21:55:11 -0800
From: "Stephen A. Berger, M.D." <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>

I ran this through GIDEON. Among several compatible diseases the
software lists:
Ehrlichiosis (both granulocytic and monocytic)
Colorado tick fever (known to occur in New Mexico)
Relapsing fever
Leptospirosis
Legionellosis (Pontiac fever)
Plague
Brucellosis
Dengue
Tularemia and
Q fever.
--
Steve Berger
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
***
[3
Date: Mon, 14 Dec 1998 12:13:48 -0800
From: "WILLIAM K. REISEN" <arbo@lightspeed.net>
Organization: ARBOVIRUS FIELD STATION

I agree that dengue could be suspect here. Recently, _Ae. aegypti_
has colonized parts of Arizona. Has any checked in New Mexico?
***
[4
Date: Mon, 14 Dec 1998 14:07:20 EST
From: AlaskaRay@aol.com

All the symptoms described in these cases are consistent with
ehrlichiosis and the timing is correct for a tick borne disease.
I've never heard of pain being such a prominent symptom in every
case, as described, but it certainly is a known symptom of
ehrlichiosis, along with abdominal pain, thrombocytopenia,
leukopenia, fever, chills, headache, etc.
I would be interested to know if they checked for ehrlichiosis or any
of the patients responded to doxycycline as treatment.
--
Raymond Weinstein, MD
Dale City, Va.
AlaskaRay@aol.com
***
